    "It is commonly used in finite temperature field theory, where the two endpoints are identified following an imaginary excursion of -iβ, rather than extending to ±i∞, in order to compute averages in the Gibbs ensembles e -βH, see for example [29].",
    "At zero-temperature, the formalism simplifies and naturally reproduces Cutkosky-like cutting rules [30], as will become clear in the calculations below.",
